"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634023","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Department does not collect the data requested.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-16T17:15:57.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634023/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634023/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much processing unsuccessful planning applications has cost local authorities in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","52636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634024","Home Office","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Government published our Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) Strategy in March 2016, which announced increased funding of £80 million from 2016 to 2020 to protect women and girls from violence, including support for refuges and other accommodation-based services, funding to national helplines, and from 2017, the launch of the VAWG Transformation Fund.</p><p>We are committed to working across Government to deliver the commitments outlined in the Strategy. The Home Office is leading work across Government to support local commissioning of services to victims and survivors of VAWG. We will set out a clear blueprint for local action though a new National Statement of Expectations and Commissioning Toolkit, which will be available to local commissioning bodies and groups. We currently plan to publish the National Statement of Expectations before the end of this year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-17T17:06:31.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634024/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634024/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-11","Crimes of Violence: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Government plans to publish the National Statement of Expectations to provide a framework for the local commissioning of services relating to violence against women and girls.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","52629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634025","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>We have provided £1.18 million to help establish 118 Coastal Community Teams along the English coast to empower local communities to drive forward renewal in their coastal towns. Every Team has produced an Economic Plan setting out both the short term and longer term priorities to promote jobs, tourism and economic growth. I will shortly be announcing more Coastal Community Teams.</p><p>We are also supporting our coastal towns to create jobs and investment. Under the Coastal Communities Fund the government has invested £125 million in over 200 projects across the UK to date, including £92 million which was invested in England. Over 60% of the grant awards by number and value have supported tourism and hospitality projects in coastal towns. We have identified a further £90 million to support more Coastal Community Fund projects.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-11-21T17:49:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634025/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634025/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Regeneration: Coastal Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what support his Department makes available for renewal for coastal towns with a significant tourism industry.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634026","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>The Secretary of State regularly meets with local government and listens to their views on the UK vote to leave the EU. Local government is engaged with government and is contributing to its work to inform future negotiations with the EU.</p><p>The UK’s decision to leave the EU is a chance for us to develop opportunities for local communities across England, and local government has a key role in ensuring that we are able to make the most of this opportunity.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-21T17:47:12.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634026/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634026/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what role the Government plans that local government will play in the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634027","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Government has noted the conclusions of the report by the Institute for Public Policy Research report on Roma communities. The UK does have a strong legal framework which protects all individuals, including Roma, from racial and other forms of discrimination and hate crime, and will continue to do so after the United Kingdom leaves the European Union.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-18T13:24:44.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634027/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634027/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the Institute for Public Research report on Roma communities and Brexit: integrating and empowering Roma communities in the UK, published on 24 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","52675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634028","Department of Health","false","2016-11-21","<p>Social care continues to be a key priority for the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Spending Review as a whole looked at the pressures on local government over the Spending Review period and particular attention was paid to adult social care services. Spending Review decisions on social care services took into account a range of financial and economic factors, including independent academic modelling of future demand for services.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of the Spending Review announced in November 2015, the Government is giving local authorities access to up to £3.5 billion of new support for social care by 2019/20. This should mean local government has access to the funding to increase social care spending in real terms by the end of the Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the current Relative Needs Formula does take into account demographics and seeks to measure need for state-funded care, and thus takes into account population need, the proportion of the population who are below the income and wealth means test threshold and the level of informal care support available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has commissioned a review of the formulae that we use for the Relative Needs Formula. This review is so that we can incorporate more recent and detailed data and statistical techniques. The researchers are currently writing up the research and this will be published in due course.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","52671","2016-11-21T16:17:17.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634028/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634028/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-11","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the future level of demand for social care; and what steps he is taking to ensure that that level of demand can be met.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","52670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634029","Department of Health","false","2016-11-21","<p>Social care continues to be a key priority for the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Spending Review as a whole looked at the pressures on local government over the Spending Review period and particular attention was paid to adult social care services. Spending Review decisions on social care services took into account a range of financial and economic factors, including independent academic modelling of future demand for services.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of the Spending Review announced in November 2015, the Government is giving local authorities access to up to £3.5 billion of new support for social care by 2019/20. This should mean local government has access to the funding to increase social care spending in real terms by the end of the Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the current Relative Needs Formula does take into account demographics and seeks to measure need for state-funded care, and thus takes into account population need, the proportion of the population who are below the income and wealth means test threshold and the level of informal care support available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has commissioned a review of the formulae that we use for the Relative Needs Formula. This review is so that we can incorporate more recent and detailed data and statistical techniques. The researchers are currently writing up the research and this will be published in due course.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","52670","2016-11-21T16:17:17.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634029/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634029/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-11","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the funding gap in social care on the adequate provision of appropriate social care.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","52671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634030","Department of Health","false","2016-11-21","<p>The Department of Health is engaged with colleagues in the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure that the needs of social care providers and those in ineed of social care services are taken into account as we exit from the EU.</p><p>The Government has made clear it wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living here, and the only circumstances in which that would not be possible is if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected in return.</p><p>The Department is aware that our challenge, working alongside stakeholders in the adult social care sector, is to ensure the workforce has the right number of people to meet increasing demands, with the right skills, knowledge and behaviours to deliver quality, compassionate care.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-21T16:15:42.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634030/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634030/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-11","Social Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the number of social care workers over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","52672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634031","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>My department has published an explanatory note on the method of allocation of the Transition Grant for 2016/17. A copy has been placed in the library of both Houses and it available to view at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510870/Explanatory_note_on_the_allocation_of_the_Transition_Grant.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510870/Explanatory_note_on_the_allocation_of_the_Transition_Grant.pdf</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-21T17:52:20.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634031/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634031/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by which formula the £150 million transition grant was allocated to local authorities; and what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of that grant in achieving its aims.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634032","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>Under the scheme, local authorities sign up to accept refugees on a voluntary basis. The last set of statistics, published on 25 August 2016 showed that between the start of October 2015 and the end of June 2016, 2,646 people were resettled under the scheme across 118 different local authorities. The quarterly migration statistics set out how many people have been resettled in each authority under the scheme. The resettlement programme has sufficient pledges of places from local authorities across the UK to resettle 20,000 vulnerable Syrians and will continue to work closely with them to turn those pledges into places.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-21T17:54:55.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634032/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634032/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have agreed to be part of the Syrian Resettlement Programme.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634033","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>344 councils accepted the multi-year settlement offer and published efficiency plans by 14 October. We will publish details of which councils they were, and the 10 councils that chose not to apply, at the provisional local government finance settlement shortly.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-21T17:47:45.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634033/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634033/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities (a) have and (b) have not made applications for a multi-year financial settlement.","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634034","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>Devolution Deals are, and will remain, a key part of our plan to support growth up and down the country as we build an economy that works for everyone. To date, the government has adopted a bottom-up and iterative approach to agreeing devolution – through a “deal-making” mechanism. This process allows local areas to develop devolution proposals through the basis of local consent and dialogue.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-11-21T17:46:23.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634034/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634034/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Mayors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's policy is on establishing new city region mayors after May 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","52503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634035","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-21","<p>There is no requirement for local authorities to hold information on their tenants who receive assistance under the cavity insulation guarantee scheme.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-21T17:49:48.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634035/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634035/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-11","Council Housing: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information local authorities are required to hold on tenants of their properties who receive assistance under the cavity insulation guarantee scheme.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","52521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634036","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-16","<p>Under its Universal Service obligations, BT must provide public call boxes in order to meet the reasonable needs of users in terms of geographical coverage, the number of public call boxes and the quality of call box services. The Government provides the powers for Ofcom to set such conditions under section 45 of the Communications Act 2003.</p><p> </p><p>Compliance with Ofcom regulations is a matter for Ofcom and any evidence that BT is not complying with its published criteria should be presented to Ofcom to investigate.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-16T16:57:58.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634036/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634036/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-11","Public Telephones: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government takes to monitor how BT complies with Ofcom regulations in maintaining public telephone boxes and ensuring that those telephone boxes remain operational.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","52533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634037","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Enfield North constituency has 43,183 premises and we estimate from the available supplier data that coverage will reach around 99.3% by the end of commercial roll-out, or approximately 42,800, will have access to superfast broadband.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is encouraging the commercial sector to extend coverage across cities. BT has announced £50 million of investment in new commercial coverage, much of which will be aimed at London, and Virgin Media has announced a demand led investment programme of £3 billion over the next few years. There are also many other active suppliers in London.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of commercially-led delivery and public funding in areas which are not commercially viable, superfast broadband coverage across the UK now reaches 90% of premises, providing access to speeds of more than 24Mbps. Coverage is on track to increase to 95% of premises by December 2017. Furthermore, the Government is committed to a Universal Service Obligation, so all premises in the country will have access to broadband at a speed of 10Mbps with the mechanism to do this, the Digital Economy Bill, in place by the end of this Parliament.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-17T11:31:28.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634037/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634037/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-11","Broadband: Enfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on the roll-out of superfast broadband in (a) Enfield North constituency and (b) the London Borough of Enfield.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","52544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634038","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-16","<p>National Citizen Service is for all young people, regardless of background. Financial support is available to ensure that the programme is accessible to all.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, 17% of NCS participants were eligible for free school meals, compared with around 10% of young people of the same age in the general population.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-16T11:21:09.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634038/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634038/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-11","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many National Citizen Service 2015 graduates were eligible for free school meals.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","52581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634039","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Department for Transport has undertaken an economic assessment of the impact of a new runway at Heathrow at national level, taking account of all regions. People in the North of England can expect to take advantage of new destinations, extra seats and increased frequency of service created by increased capacity at Heathrow.</p>​ ​<p>The Prime Minister's Tourism Action Plan, which features Transport as a key area, sets out how this Government plans to boost Tourism to the UK; and the Discover England Fund is creating world-class tourism products and experiences throughout the whole of England that will cater to the needs and aspirations of international visitors.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-16T17:22:18.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634039/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634039/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-11","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the potential economic effects on the North of England of increased inbound tourism as a result of Heathrow Airport expansion.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","52624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634040","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>&quot;A Better Defence Estate&quot; is a military-led report.</p><p>The number of civilian jobs and service personnel that will be based at Leuchars on completion of the &quot;A Better Defence Estate&quot; review is yet to be determined. As outlined in the Strategy, Leuchars will be one of the primary hubs in which the Defence Estate will consolidate in Scotland. Assessment studies in the next 12 to 18 months will clarify how Leuchars will be utilised and therefore the number of civilian and military personnel who will be based there.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","52659","2016-11-16T15:59:29.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634040/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634040/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civilian jobs will be attached to Leuchars on completion of the Better Defence Estate review, published in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","52660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634041","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>&quot;A Better Defence Estate&quot; is a military-led report.</p><p>The number of civilian jobs and service personnel that will be based at Leuchars on completion of the &quot;A Better Defence Estate&quot; review is yet to be determined. As outlined in the Strategy, Leuchars will be one of the primary hubs in which the Defence Estate will consolidate in Scotland. Assessment studies in the next 12 to 18 months will clarify how Leuchars will be utilised and therefore the number of civilian and military personnel who will be based there.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","52660","2016-11-16T15:59:29.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634041/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634041/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many service personnel will be based at Leuchars on completion of the Better Defence Estate review, published in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","52659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634042","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-21","<p>The payments made to Red Snapper cover two contract periods and can be broken down, by financial year (FY), as follows:</p><p>First contract period (February 2013 - January 2016)</p><p>FY 2013-14 - £4.4 million</p><p>FY 2014-15 - £6.8 million</p><p>FY 2015-16 - £4.9 million</p><p>Current contract period (February 2016 - September 2016)</p><p>FY 2015-16 - £0.9 million</p><p>FY 2016-17 - £3.8 million</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-21T16:19:38.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634042/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634042/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Red Snapper Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide a breakdown of the £20.8 million paid to Red Snapper since 2013.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","52665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634043","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-21","<p>Yes. During the first contract period with Red Snapper for the provision of staff for the Iraq Historic Allegations Team (February 2013 - January 2016), accommodation expenses, where applicable, were claimed by Red Snapper personnel from the Ministry of Defence and paid through the company. These expenses are included within the total amount of the £2.97 million claimed by contracted personnel. Under the current contract all such claims are a matter for Red Snapper.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-21T16:20:12.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634043/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634043/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Red Snapper Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether Red Snapper has received any additional payments from his Department for travel or accommodation expenses.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","52666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634044","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review (SDSR) 2015 set clear targets for the required number of trained Regular and Reserve Service personnel in April 2020, including 82,000 Regulars in the Army, 30,450 in the Royal Navy/Royal Marines and 31,750 in the Royal Air Force. Key details of the SDSR 2015 targets can be found at the following address: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/494895/SDSR_2015_Booklet_vers_15.pdf</p><p>The Ministry of Defence undertakes detailed manpower planning for the Armed Forces but does not publish interim projections.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-16T16:10:49.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634044/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634044/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what projections he has made of the size of the (a) Army, (b) Royal Navy and (c) Royal Air Force in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","52661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634045","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>I was informed of the shortfall in funding for the Armed Forces Pension Scheme on 20 October 2016.</p><p>As per my Written Statement, Her Majesty's Treasury have remedied their error. No former or serving Service personnel have been affected.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-16T16:06:38.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634045/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634045/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armed Forces: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Written Statement of 8 November 2016, WS 246, on which date Ministers of his Department were informed of the shortfall in funding for the Armed Forces Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","52701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634046","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-21","<p>The total amount claimed for expenses by contracted personnel recruited through Red Snapper is £2.97 million.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-21T16:20:43.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634046/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634046/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Red Snapper Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much from the public purse has been claimed by the 127 investigators recruited by Red Snapper to date.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","52667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634047","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-21","<p>Pay and other conditions of service for Red Snapper personnel are a matter for them. The Ministry of Defence makes payments to Red Snapper based on an hourly charge rate which varies depending on the qualifications and experience required for each investigative role.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-21T16:21:24.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634047/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634047/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Red Snapper Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much from the public purse has been paid by the 127 investigators recruited by Red Snapper to date.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","52668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634048","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-21","<p>Red Snapper are contracted to provide the Iraq Historic Allegations Team with appropriately qualified investigative personnel in accordance with the requirements set out in the contract. The number of recruiting or other support staff that Red Snapper employ to meet that requirement is a matter for them. No recruiters are employed under the terms of their contract with the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-11-21T16:21:56.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634048/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634048/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Iraq Historic Allegations Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many recruiters at Red Snapper are employed under the contract awarded by the Iraq Historic Allegations Team.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","52669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634049","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>The error by Her Majesty's Treasury has not led to any further shortfalls in funding for other services in the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-16T16:11:23.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634049/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634049/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Ministry of Defence: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Written Statement of 8 November 2016, WS 249, whether the error referred to in that Statement has led to shortfalls in funding for other services provided by his Department.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","52702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634050","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>Armed Forces Pension Scheme recipients were not affected by the recent error by Her Majesty's Treasury.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-16T16:07:22.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634050/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634050/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armed Forces: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department's recent shortfall in funding for the Armed Forces Pension Scheme (AFPS) has prohibited AFPS recipients from drawing on their pension.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","52703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634051","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>The printing error was made by Her Majesty's Treasury who are reviewing their internal processes to ensure such mistakes do not occur again. In future, the Ministry of Defence will have sight of the Armed Forces Pension Scheme figures prior to publication by Her Majesty's Treasury .</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-16T16:09:15.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634051/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634051/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armed Forces Compensation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Written Statement of 8 November 2016, WS 249, what steps his Department is taking to identify the source of the inadvertent publishing error referred to; and what steps he is taking to ensure such an error does not happen again.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","52704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634052","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>Ministry of Defence (MOD) housing supports serving members of the Armed Forces and their families. Where housing is no longer needed, MOD policy is to release it in accordance with Treasury Guidelines. Any sale must achieve best value for money for the Department, and this is usually achieved via the open market. Development of any MOD site, once sold, is a matter for the purchaser.</p><p>The vast majority of our Service leavers make a smooth transition into civilian life. The MOD provides education and support to Service personnel due to leave the Armed Forces to prepare them for the transition to civilian life. This includes education and advice about future housing options, delivered by the Joint Service Housing Advice Office. In addition, the Government has put in place significant support for those who find the process difficult, including through the £40 million Veterans Accommodation Fund which opened in 2014.</p><p>Service leavers have priority in applying for Government funded shared ownership schemes, which has now been extended to 24 months after service. Those injured in Service should also have preferential access to appropriate housing schemes, as well as assistance with necessary adaptations to private housing or Service accommodation whilst serving.</p><p>The MOD Referral Scheme also provides support to Service leavers and their families, with social housing offers made directly by housing associations and other charitable housing providers following discharge.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-16T16:10:05.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634052/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634052/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Veterans: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what account he is taking of veterans' needs in the redevelopment of his Department's housing sites.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","52586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634053","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>The first vehicles from the AJAX fleet will be delivered to the British Army in April 2017, with deliveries scheduled to be complete in 2025.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-16T16:04:00.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634053/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634053/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the timetable is for the full order of Ajax armoured vehicles to be delivered to the British Army.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","52582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634054","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-16","<p>AJAX vehicles will transform the Army's medium armour and advanced intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance (ISTAR) capability. They will be able to conduct sustained, expeditionary, full spectrum operations with a minimal logistic footprint, in a wide range of combat situations and potential future operating environments. As it is brought into service, AJAX will undergo rigorous trials and experimentation to understand and further optimise its combat effectiveness.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-11-16T16:03:20.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634054/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/634054/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-11","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Ajax armoured vehicle in combat situations.","false","Biography information for Wayne David","Caerphilly","Wayne David","52583"
