"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631918","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-14","<p>UK funding has helped build Palestinian institutions and promote economic growth so that any future Palestinian state will be a prosperous and effective partner for peace. DFID’s previous financial assistance to the PA was governed by a Memorandum of Understanding which reaffirms the PA’s commitment to non-violence and a negotiated solution to the conflict. As the Development Secretary has recently taken up her position, she is undertaking a full examination of DFID’s programme in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, including our support to the PA.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-14T15:51:05.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631918/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631918/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-08","Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that aid provided to the Palestinian Authority does not fund radicalisation.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","52399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631919","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-14","<p>The eligibility of the UK’s Overseas Territories to receive UK aid is not linked to the UK's EU membership and is unaffected by the UK's decision to leave the EU. Eligibility for UK aid funding is defined in the International Development Act 2002 and is dependent on a recipient country or territory being on the list of recipients of official development assistance (ODA) held by the Development Assistance Committee (DAC) of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). Details of the list are available on the DAC website: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/documentupload/DAC%20List%20of%20ODA%20Recipients%202014%20final.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.oecd.org/dac/stats/documentupload/DAC%20List%20of%20ODA%20Recipients%202014%20final.pdf</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-14T17:14:35.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631919/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631919/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-08","British Overseas Territories: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to adjust the eligibility requirements of overseas aid funding so that the Overseas Territories are eligible for UK aid funding once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","52401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631920","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-14","<p>My Department provides funding to humanitarian organisations that work to promote safe and healthy environments for people in refugee camps across the world. Camps are not the preferred option for refugees and most refugees live outside of camps. DFID supports organisations that work specially with mothers and infants in camp situations including UNICEF, Save the Children and UNHCR.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-14T15:53:12.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631920/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631920/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-08","Migrant Camps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that infants can feed in a safe and clean environment in refugee camps.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","52342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631921","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-16","<p>The number of personal independence payment appeal tribunals found in favour of the claimant (and as a proportion of those cleared at hearing) is published by the Ministry of Justice in the ‘Tribunals and Gender Recognition Statistics Quarterly’ on gov.uk.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-16T12:01:55.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631921/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631921/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-08","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many personal independence payment appeal tribunals have found in favour of the claimant in (a) 2015 and (b) 2016 to date; and what proportion that was of the number of such appeal cases.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","52324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631922","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-18","<p>Oldham County Court is scheduled to close between July and September 2017. Work in preparation for this closure is ongoing and accurate estimates will only be available once this is completed. Estimates of lease surrender costs are commercially sensitive for HMCTS and the landlord and would therefore not be published in advance of the surrender of the lease, even where an estimate was held.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-18T12:31:31.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631922/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631922/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-08","County Courts: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate her Department has made of the (a) relocation costs, (b) lease surrender costs, (c) legal fees and dilapidations and (d) other costs associated with the planned closure of Oldham County Court.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","52339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/631923","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-12","<p>NOMS takes public protection and escapes from prison extremely seriously. An immediate investigation, independent of the prison, is completed following any escape to determine what went wrong and to learn lessons for the future. The vast majority of those who escape are quickly re-captured by the police and charged and prosecuted.</p><p>KPI escapes<sup>1</sup> from establishment by offence between 2011/12 to 2015/16 are published on gov.uk. The security category of the prison is also provided. Figures for 2010/11 are not published; there was one KPI escape from a Cat B establishment in 2010/11. The prisoner who escaped was serving a sentence for theft. All prisoners who escaped between 2010/11 and 2015/16 have been returned to custody following the incident.</p><p>Absconds take place only from open (Cat D) prisons. Absconds between 2011/12 and 2015/16 by the main offence of the prisoner at the time of the abscond are published on gov.uk. Figures for 2010/11 are not published and are provided below. Three prisoners who absconded from open prison in 2010/11 were still unlawfully at large on 30 April 2016; all other absconders have been returned to custody.</p><p> </p><p><sup>NOTE 1</sup> An escape is deemed to be a KPI escape if (i) the prisoner is at liberty for 15 minutes or more before recapture or (ii) an offence is committed during an escape lasting less than 15 minutes.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Absconds by offence<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>ALL OFFENCES</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>235</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Violence against the person</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sexual offences</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Robbery</p></td><td><p>69</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Theft offences</p></td><td><p>66</